column168: On March 4,2020, at approximately 7:00 AM CST, facility personnel at the above- referenced R+L Carriers (R+L) terminal were off loading shipments when personnel discovered one (1) 5-gallon pail containing corrosive liquid that was damaged by a nail during transit. As a result of the nail puncture, approximately one(1) gallon of product released to the concrete terminal surface. At approximately 7:15 AM CST, a representative from R+L retained Cura Emergency Services (CES) to manage the environmental remediation on their behalf. Based on the available information, the CES incident manager dispatched a crew from HazChem Environmental (HCE) to assess and remediate the site as necessary. At approximately 9:15 AM CST, a crew from HCE arrived onsite. Following a site inspection, crews identified approximately one (1) gallon of a corrosive liquid that had released from a 5-gallon pale. HCE personnel deployed a granular neutralizer to the corrosive liquid and worked it in with hand tools. All impacted materials were collected and containerized within one (1) 30-gallon poly drum for transport and disposal. HCE personnel noted no additional corrective actions were required onsite and demobilized.

At about 1430 hours on 03/02/2020, The East yard Carman discovered that Tank Car UTLX 201327 which was on track 33 East Departure was leaking. Inspection revealed that 1/2 gallon of Mineral Spirits had leaked out of the Liquid Valve due to it being partially open and the plug did not have the thread sealed off. Response Management Services was contacted 708.612.5922 or 219.363.9835. They responded to the scene and arrived at 1500 Hrs on 03/02/2020. Valve was fully closed and thread sealed off. Area was cleaned up.
column169: Inspect that product is properly prepared for transport.

column168: On March 5,2020, at approximately 10:15 a.m. CST, personnel at the above-referenced facility owned by R+L Carriers(RLC) discovered a 55-gallon drum of white paint(UN1263) had been damaged due to unknown circumstances. As a result, approximately 20 gallons of white paint was released to the trailer interior and below concrete surfaces of the parking lot. RLC retained Cura to manage the cleanup, and Cura dispatched a crew from Lone Star Hazmat (LSH). At approximately 11:20 a.m. CST, a crew from LSH arrived onsite. Following a site assessment, LSH personnel noted approximately 20 gallons of white paint released from a damaged 55-gallon drum to the trailer interior and below concrete surfaces of the parking lot. The crew moved cargo from the trailer and wiped down with absorbent pads as necessary. LSH personnel then deployed granular absorbents to the white paint-impacted trailer interior to solidify and worked in with hand tools. The crew then degreased and pressure washed the trailer interior and concrete surfaces of the parking lot until no visual or olfactory evidence of white paint remained onsite. All white paint-impacted material and rinsate was collected in one(1) 95-gallon overpack, one(1) 55-gallon drum, and one(1) vacuum trailer for transport and disposal as non-hazardous. LSH personnel secured the site and demobilized.
Shipment was being screened. Outer box did not contain indicating labels, nor did inner box that contained the product

column168: On March 6,2020, at approximately 7:45 am CST, a representative for R+L Carriers(RLC) observed a damaged pale of UN1263 paint at door 29 at the above-referenced location. Due to the damage, approximately 10 gallons of product was released to the trailer floor. RLC retained Cura Emergency Services, L.C.(CES) to manage the cleanup. CES dispatched a crew from First Call Environmental(FCE) to assess and remediate. At approximately 10:15 am CST, a crew from FC arrived on-site. Following a site assessment, FC personnel noted two(2) 5-gallon pales of UN1263 were damaged due to a load shift and released approximately 10 gallons to the trailer floor. Crews utilized a fork lift to safely remove the contents of the trailer to complete remediation. As items were moved out, they were wiped clean of any residual product. FC personnel deployed a neutralizing agent to the release liquid. Once neutralized, granular absorbents were deployed and worked in using hand tools. All UN1263 impacted material and two(2) damaged pales were collected and containerized in two(2) 55-gallon drums for transport and disposal. FC personnel no further actions required on-site and crews demobilized.

On March 10, 2020, at approximately 1:30 p.m. CDT, a tractor-trailer operated by R+L Carriers (R +L) was parked at the above-referenced location when the driver observed a cargo leak from the trailer. Upon inspection, four (4) 55-gallon drums of UN1760 nitric acid were tipped over during transpon. One of the drums leaked approximately 5 gallons of nitric acid from the bung to the trailer interior and concrete surface below. R+L retained Cura Emergency Services, L.C. (CES) to manage the cleanup. CES dispatched a crew from Hull's Environmental Services (HES) for the remediation. Crews uprighted the drums and observed the release originated from a loose bung cap on one(1) of the 55-gallon drums. HES deployed granular absorbents to the release and swept them in with hand tools. All impacted surfaces were neutralized and wiped down. All spent absorbents and cleanup materials were collected and containerized into one (1) 30-gallon drum for transport and disposal. HES rescured the drums in the trailer for transport. Once the cleanup was complete, HES secured the scene and demobilized.

column168: During offloading the consignee informed our driver that the fuel was not drained from the heaters (dangerous goods in machinery, UN3363) and they had leaked in the back of the vehicle. Fuel had leaked out of the wooden crates holding the heaters and released an estimated 1-2 gallons of fuel on the trailer floor. No hazmat paperwork was provided and the freight was loaded, secured and sealed by staff at a secure facility for the HHS/CDC so the driver was not able to view the freight making us unaware of the hazmat on board. The consignee removed and accepted the freight, but advised that would not clean the material from the trailer. FedEx Custom Critical contacted a local agency for cleanup and disposal of the released fuel at the consignee's location.
column169: The calling party, Jack Darlington, took responsibility advising that the staff is aware that the fuel needs to be drained and supply hazmat paperwork. He advised that he would follow up with their staff for additional training.

column168: DG/SPILL CLEAN UP AGENT WAS CALLED OVER TO INVESTIGATE WHAT PEOPLE BELIEVED TO BE A SMOLDERING PACKAGE AT THE END OF A BELT. DG AGENT MOVED PACKAGE AWAY FROM EMPLOYEES AND TO A SAFE LOCATION WHERE HE SAW THE BOTTOM OF THE PACKAGE WAS TURNING BLACK AND THE FLOOR OF THE CONTAINER HE HAD PLACED THE PACKAGE IN FOR CONTAINMENT AND MOVEMENT WAS BECOMING DAMAGED; WHAT WE WOULD LATER DETERMINE AS BEING CORROSIVE DAMAGE FROM THE CONTENTS INSIDE THE PACKAGE. PACKAGE USED FOR SHIPMENT WAS NOT UN SPEC PACKAGING, NOR WERE CONTENTS DECLARED AS DANGEROUS GOODS, HOWEVER, THE BOX CONTAINED WHAT THE SPILL CLEAN UP AGENTS DETERMINED AS SUCH THROUGH PAPERWORK AND LABELING OF BOTTLES: UN3407 MAGNESIUM CHLORIDE (MIXTURES) CLASS 5.1, UN1824 SODIUM HYDROXIDE / SODIUM CHLORIDE CLASS 8, UN1789 HYDROCHLORIC ACID (2 BOTTLES, 1 BROKE) CLASS 8, AND A POUCH WITH VIALS INSIDE CONTAINING A WHITE GRANULAR SUBSTANCE. SPILL CLEAN UP AGENTS ISOLATED THE SPILL, BEING SURE TO PLACE KNOWN INCOMPATIBLE ITEMS IN DIFFERENT SALAVE DRUMS. PACKAGES ARE BEING HELD AT LOCATION PENDING REVIEW.

column168: On 03/03/2020, SNEU 600239 was reported leaking by hub personnel from BNSF Los Angeles IMF upon being deramped from the train.  Exterior inspection revealed previous repairs to the belly of the tank was allowing the UN1903 Disinfectants, Liquid corrosive N.O.S to leak out in multiple places.

UPGZ 511646 was reported leaking by hub personnel from BNSF San Bernardino IMF upon deramp. This unit was billed as carrying hazardous materials. In the interest of safety, the unit was placed on hold and placed in the containment pit pending interior inspection. United Pumping was called to remediate the load. Interior inspection revealed a mixed load of freight with minimal lateral voids and no dunnage. The unit was unloaded by United Pumping and the origin of the leak was a crack in the bottom of a metal 55 gal drum of Specialist Cleaning Solvent (Flammable Liquid). Approximately 52 gallons of the solvent was able to leak out with more than half reaching the ground. How the drum cracked could not be determined.

column168: While unloading a shipment that was delivered by our customer (TCI) to Veolia's 10 day in transit  facility Veolia employees noticed a leaking drum containing PCB oil. The closure ring and lid bungs  were discovered to be loose which allowed liquid to be released from the drum. It was also discovered  that the remaining load of the PCB drums were not properly closed. The spill was cleaned up using  diesel fuel and the leaking drum was overpacked. The remaining drums were inspected, wiped down  and verified that they were rated to contain liquid material. All rings and bungs were properly closed as  appropriate.
column169: Veolia's customer, TCI was notified of the incident and recommended that for future shipments they  need to ensure they are using the proper rated packaging for hazmat shipments and that all  packaging are closed in accordance with the manufacturer's closure instructions.

On March 17, 2020 XPO Logistics notified ERTS of a release of PM-4082 200PF from a 55 gallon metal drum due to a forklift puncture. ERTS dispatched EnviroServe to conduct cleanup activities. At 0521 EST, contractors arrived on site and confirmed (2) 55 gallon drums released approximately 75 gallons of product. Approximately 80% of the product evaporated prior to their arrival. Absorbents were utilized to clean the impacted areas. All waste was containerized into an 85 gallon over pack and (2) 55 gallon metal drums. All waste was left on site for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: On 3-21-2020, at 1343hrs. personnel in the CSXT Avon Yard discovered UTLX 903507, a loaded tank car of Acetaldehyde having a strong chemical odor coming from the top. The car was isolated and Eastman Chemical was notified.  CHEMTREC report# 2020-032100085. Hepaco, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the pressure relief valve leaking. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Tony Nicks 314-413-7339. Contractor personnel applied a Midland Kit to the pressure relief device, as attempts at replacing the O-rings failed stop the vapor release. 03-31-2020 Hepaco conducted a transfer and clean and purge of UTLX 903507.  On 4-06-2020, EnviroServe, a CSXT emergency response contractor, removed the defective pressure relief valve and found the device actuated and the seat “O” ring was pinched between the body preventing the valve seat from sealing correctly.

column168: At 1022 ET, ERTS was notified by Brandy Clark with Trimac regarding a release of a Resin Solution. The caller stated the release was caused by the driver unloading the product into the wrong off-loading tube.  The caller stated the release has been contained to the concrete and advised that an estimated that 50-60 gallons of product was released to the concrete containment pit only.  At 1231 ET EnviroServe (environmental contractor) is now onsite and advised that up to 60 gallons of product was released to a 30' x 40' area of the concrete. It was advised that minimal product has splashed outside of the containment area. It was advised that it appears that facility personnel have attempted to clean this area but that the concrete is stained. EnviroServe personnel utilized granular absorbents to solidify the free liquids. EnviroServe personnel utilized an acetone solution to clean the residual staining. All waste will be taken for profiling and pending disposal

column168: On 3-18-2020 at 0900 hrs., while a train was passing through the Brewster Yard, the engineer noticed that while a train was switching on an adjacent track, tank car UTLX 64052 leaked from the manway lid.  It was reported to the yard master and while I was out of town I, John Vergis Hazardous Materials/Environmental Officer for the WLE, had the car set to the shop for further investigation.  When I got on top the car I had seen that a small amount of Asphalt did release from the Manway Lid.  I removed Seal Number 0333999 from the Manyway Lid to prepare for opening the Lid.  I then removed seal number 0333997 from the Breadbox lid so that i could vent the car before opening the Manyway Lid.  I opened the Manyway Lid and found that the Manway gasket had about a 1/2 inch peice missing from it which is what cause it to leak.  I replaced the gasket and secured the lid and installed new seal 971765.  I then secured the vapor valve inside the breadbox since I used it to vent the car and then installed new Seal 971768 on the lid after closing it.  I then released the car for transportation.  NARRI 5(5+0+0)x(2+0)=27                                                             Cause Code: 209

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Non-Reclosing
column168: On March 8, 2020, at 10:50 hours personnel in the CSXT Kingsport, TN yard reported GATX 6570, a tank car loaded with Sulfuric Acid was suspected to be leaking from the top of the car.  The car was isolated and the shipper, Southern States Chemical, was notified via CHEMTREC Report #2020-0308-00034.  Marion Environmental, Inc. (MEI), a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and confirmed the car was leaking from the pressure relief vent assembly.  MEI found the rupture disc retaining was not installed, the surge protection sleeve and rupture disc were not present, and noted a crack in the vent assembly.  Contractor personnel installed a rupture disc and secured the rupture disc retaining ring to stop the release.  The car was held at CSX Kingsport, TN pending component replacement by a certified mobile repair unit.

column42: NITRIC ACID OTHER THAN RED FUMING, WITH AT LEAST 65 PERCENT, BUT NOT MORE THAN 70 PERCENT NITRIC ACID
column168: Highway Transport driver arrived to consignee (Blue Bell Creameries). Driver checked in with consignee and was instructed where to unload and which fill line to connect to. Consignee gave our driver permission to move forward with the off-loading process. Driver connected his hoses to the trailer and then to the fill line of the consignees storage tank. (Note) consignee's fill line was of PVC material. Highway Transport's driver checked for leaks once all connections were made and verified no leaks with the consignee's representative. Once the leak test was completed our driver opened discharge valves on trailer and on the consignee fill line and started to apply pressure to the cargo tank.  Approximately five minutes into the off-load, the nipple on the consignee fill line broke completely off, causing product to be discharged on the ground. Our driver immediately shut down the flow of product from the cargo tank and closed off the valve on the consignee fill line. Both driver and consignee laid down spill pads and created a barrier to keep the product inside the containment area. Once the cleanup was completed, the consignee repaired the fill line and our driver safely finished off-loading remaining product without and further product loss or incidents. No one was exposed nor injured doing the release.  Blue Bell took full responsibility for the cleanup and release. Once our driver completed the off-load he was cleared for release by consignee and Highway Transport.
column169: No. Highway Transport did not suggest nor advise consignee of any changes in methods, design, or any other procedures They presently had in place for off-loading products at their facility.

On March 26, 2020, at 14:30 hours personnel in the CSXT Kingsport, TN yard reported product leaking from the top of UTLX 205356, a loaded tank car of Acetone.  The car was isolated and the shipper, Advansix, was notified via CHEMTREC Report #2020-0326-00230.  Marion Environmental, Inc. (MEI), a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched and found the release was due to loose flange bolts on the tank car’s liquid induction line valve body.  MEI was able to tighten the six (6) valve body bolts and stop the release.  The issue’s identified and corrective actions were communicated to shipper’s representative: Mr. Larry Buffy.  The car was held out of transportation pending the shipper obtaining an OTMA or having a certified facility perform repair and qualification on the valve.

column168: A shipment was received at the Lemont Heritage Transport facility on 03/18/2020. The waste was weighed and moved to a trailer on 03/18/2020. On 3/20/2020, a routine inspection of the Lemont Heritage Transport facility was performed. During this inspection, a trailer was found to have a black liquid pool underneath. Upon further inspection and investigation, it was determined that a fiberboard IBC container from Halstab was leaking 3-5 gallons of black liquid.  1. The spill was cleaned up internally.  2. The liquid inside the fiberboard IBC was absorbed using corn-cob absorbent. This changed the liquid state of the material into a solid state. 3. The hazardous solids, including those generated from the clean-up, were repackaged into a new fiberboard IBC. Since this material was solidified, the fiberboard IBC was an appropriate container type.
column169: It was determined that the material shipped was too wet for the container that it was shipped in.  The fiberboard IBC should not have been used to ship liquid material. The offeror was made aware of the instance so as to help prevent future occurances.

column168: 03/25/20, at 1039 hours, A Conductor while coupling up to the TCIX6968 a loaded tank car of Fluorosilicic Acid in the Greenwich yard Philadelphia PA was splashed with a watery substance from the top of the rail car. It was discovered that the railcar was leaking from the SALCO non resetting Vent vale on the top of the rail car. The car was isolated and Solvay Fluorides was notified by (CHEMTREC 2020032500094). The conductor received medical treatment at the scene and was transported to the hospital for evaluation and released. HEPACO, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the tank car was leaking from SALCO Vent valve. Upon inspection the valve was found to be disassembled with the rupture disk and baffle missing. the surge protector was found intact on the ground laying near the rail cars.The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Kyle Vandermolen 913-242-1187. Contractor personnel temporarily secured the railcar that will require that the SALCO valve be replaced and the railcar bubble leak test be performed by a MRU prior to being released to transportation. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1.

column169: Veolia notified the offeror of the container to let them know that it was not properly closed. In addition, Veolia has implemented a check off list for all drivers to verify that each container is properly closed  prior to pick up.  Training was completed and implementation of this new guideline was communicated to the Veolia field employees who pick up hazmat packages at offeror sites.

column168: On March 17, 2020, at approximately 03:00 a.m. CDT, R+L Carriers(R+L) personnel observed a Ieaking 180-gallon tote at the above referenced terminal due to a unsecured valve. As a result of the unsecured valve, the tote released approximately 25 gallons of paint residue to the concrete loading dock. R+L retained Cura Emergency Services, LC(CES) to manage the cleanup. CES dispatched TAS Environmental GAS) to initiate corrective actions. The crew donned the appropriate personal protective equipment(PPE) and deployed granular absorbents to the impacted concrete. TAS utilized pads to wipe down the tote and nearby pallets. The crew transferred the remaining liquid in the 180-gallon tote to one(1) 55-gallon drum for transport and disposal. TAS collected the spent absorbents into two(2) 55-gallon drums for transport and disposal. TAS secured the site and demobilized.

column168: On 03/16/2020 at approximately 07:04 pm, COC TRANSPORTATION INC.,( tractor unit #P-20 and trailer unit #9 ), was involved in a single vehicle accident/rollover while exiting (East bound I-40 at exit 198) in Flagstaff, Arizona. The vehicle attempted to make a left turn onto E. Butler Avenue where it lost control and rolled. The vehicle came to rest on the passenger side on the North side of Butler Avenue just before the Interstate 40 overpass. The tanker trailer sprung a leak when it rolled onto it’s side and the 8,787 gallons of gasoline aboard the tanker trailer caught on fire. It is currently unclear how many gallons made it to the storm drain and how many gallons of fuel burned as a result of this incident. Flagstaff Fire Department, Summit Fire Department, Highland Fire Department, Flagstaff Pulliam Airport Fire Department, Flagstaff Police Department, Guardian Medical Transport, Arizona Department of Transportation, Arizona Department of Public Safety, and the City of Flagstaff’s Streets Division all responded to the scene to block traffic, investigate the scene and control the fire. COC Transportation, Inc. was made aware of the incident by another employee of COC Transportation Inc. and the accident was promptly verified using GPS tracking. COC Transportation Inc. dispatch then attempted to reach out to the driver for verification of the accident and also contacted the COC Transportation Inc.  owners Paul Carter and Nick Carter. Nick Carter immediately contacted PERS, ( Professional Emergency Resource Service ), and Emergency Environmental Services. Meanwhile EMT transported the driver to the hospital with minor injuries and the driver was released from the hospital at approximately 11:00pm on 3/16/2020.
column169: COC Transportation has held monthly and documented all of its safety meetings with all of its employees as part of our effort to minimize all work related accidents. Following this incident and in keeping with best safe practices for Covid19 we elected to meet one on one with each driver. We covered driving defensively, HOS compliance, Pre-trip / Post-trip, and we addressed individual speeding records for the past six months. As a collective effort on behalf of management, dispatch and drivers we implemented new procedures to help facilitate a better understanding of work place safety. An email notification alert system was enacted via Verizon Connect to keep the drivers informed. The extent of each meeting entailed about 1 hour per driver.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: On March 21, 2020, at 0629 ET, ERTS was contacted by XPO Logistics Terminal XDE regarding a cargo release.  It was reported that due to a forklift accident, (1) 275-gallon metal tote of Glycol Ether (Combustible liquid, n.o.s., UN1993) was punctured, releasing approximately 250-gallons of product on to a 42' by 10' area of the trailer floor and continuing on to a 50' by 50' area of the concrete beneath the trailer.  A contractor was dispatched to clean up the release using absorbents and the proper PPE.  The remaining product was transferred into a new container to be forwarded on to the consignee.  All waste debris generated was containerized in (6) 55-gallon metal drums which were then staged, along with the damaged tote, onsite at OS&D for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: THE KAG SPECIALTY PRODUCTS GROUP, LLC DRIVER WAS PREPARING TO INITIATE HIS DELIVERY OF POTASSIUM HYDROXIDE INTO THE CUSTOMER'S STORAGE TANK. THE DRIVER NOTICED A MINOR LEAK COMING FROM THE EXTERNAL VALVE OF THE TRAILER. AS THE DRIVER WAS ATTEMPTING TO REPAIR THE EXTERNAL VALVE. POTASSIUM HYDROXIDE BEGAN TO ESCAPE FROM THE TRAILER AT A MUCH MORE RAPID PACE. THE DRIVER WAS UNABLE TO STOP THE FLOW OF PRODUCT AND APPROXIMATELY 45,125 LBS OF POTASSIUM HYDROXIDE WAS RELEASED, IT APPEARS THAT THERE WAS ALSO AN ISSUE WITH THE TRAILER'S INTERNAL VALVE THAT WAS ALLOWING PRODUCT TO ESCAPE. A PORTION OF THE SPILLED POTASSIUM HYDROXIDE WAS ABLE TO MIGRATE TO A NEARBY STORM DRAIN. HEPPAXO ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND HANDLED THE REMEDIATION. NO FURTHER ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT IS ANTICIPATED.

column168: During delivery procedure driver felt need to regauge underground storage tank using tank stick. Driver removed the hose and fitting assembly to access drop tube with tank stick. Driver failed to reconnect the hose drop fitting coupler to the tank connection and opened the delivery valve allowing product to flow through hose releasing to concrete and asphalt surfaces. Driver immediately reacted closing the delivery valve to stop the product flow. Estimated duration of valve being opened would be 5 seconds. Released product flowed down hill to a concrete storm water collection drain box designed with a contamination prevention weir system to prevent contaminates from flowing from containment box petroleum product would float on top of water within containment box. Spilled product was contained within the concrete drain containment box. Incident response included treatment of concrete and asphalt surfaces with pertoleum absorbent i e Oil Dri that was ground thruoghout affected area and then drummed for removal and disposal. Liquid contents of contaiment box petroleum water mixture  was removed via Vacuum Truck for removal and disposal. Solid contents sediment  was removed by hand shovel and drummed for removal and disposal.

column168: On 3/27/2020 this shipment was reported as Ieaking due to a broken inner package during the sort process at the MIA GTW 5815 NW 18th Street Bldg 716J Miami FL 33126. Transportation by air has been confirmed.

While loading the trailer an associate punctured the top right corner of the tote with another pallet. This caused a crack in the tote approximately 3 inches long which resulted in an estimated 10gallons of the product spilling in the trailer. The tote was immediately removed from the trailer and tilted to one side to stop the spilling. Absorbent was then put down to capture any spilled material. The trailer was cleaned out and placed on the OOS line to prevent use.
column169: The associate will go through the freight handler training module on how to load a Iinehaul trailer and The supervisor will retrain the associate on the importance of situational awareness when loading to prevent further instances of this happening.

column168: On Friday March 6th 2020 28 carboys of UN1993 Waste Flammable Liquids NOS Methanol Isopropanol) were picked up from Jersey City Medical Center They were stacked on a pallet 9 to a layer. The driver pulled over after hearing a bang in the back of the truck. Once pulled over, the driver noticed waste Ieaking out of the side of the truck, through the floor boards. Spill pads were placed on the ground to absorb Ieaking waste. An ER team was called and when they arrived on scene they overpacked the Ieaking container cleaned the inside of the truck and secured the load Our driver then continued his route.
column169: All drivers receive load securement training at the time of hire before running routes on their own Additionally, each March, drivers are retrained on load securement We will continue to stress the importance of properly securing a load before driving Our facility has recently purchased additional load straps to ensure our drivers can properly secure loads.

Driver was turning left onto Mission Ave from Hwy 59 when an unsecured IBC tote full of material slid into the delivery truck door causing the door to come upon and allowing the tote to fall onto the shoulder. The tote was punctured by the metal cage that secures the bladder in the upper right hand comer causing a 2-3 inch gash. This allowed material to leak onto the shoulder of Mission Ave. The duration of the release was less than 10 minutes as we were able to dispatch additional employees from our location less than a mile away to pull the tote upright and use commercial spill kits to contain the material to a 3x6 foot area. Patriot Environmental Services were called and dispatched to the scene to handle the clean up and disposal of contaminated soil.
column169: Immediately following this incident the shipping facility operations manager held an all manager/driver meeting to discuss DOT Hazardous Material training specifically the section regarding Load Securement under 49 CFR Part 177.834 and Subpart I(49 CFR Part 393). In addition to securing ALL loads, a refresher of Pre-trip Safety inspections, loading and unloading, SDS/ERG books, and Incident reporting was completed. The employees all signed a training sheet, as did the managers.

column168: This was offered as a multi-piece shipment or three packages. One of the boxes fell apart on the belt during the sort and out spilled inner boxes(10) with limited quantity ground marks. Each off the ten inner boxes contained 24 bottles of 118 oz of hand sanitizer. This package was not offered with any DG markings, labels or paperwork. The other 2 boxes did not contain DG. The FAA was notified and the shipment was held until later that day when it was released by FAA's Steven Redeker as these were for a nursing home and needed for humanitarian reasons. The recipient was to be notified same day that they could pick up the shipment. Some of the hand sanitizers had leaked as well. Photos were sent to the FAA.(exact packing group unknown; defaulted to PG I just to make a selection on screen- mandatory field) This hand sanitizer was homemade by the pharmacy. I
A heavy box was placed on top of the tote. The weight forced some of the liquid out of the cap. The cap was not damaged, the metal cage was bent but otherwise fine.

The KAG Specialty Products Group, LLC driver was attempting to load the tank trailer with sodium hydroxide solution. The driver failed to notice that a valve on the rear of the trailer was in the open position. As the product was being loaded into the trailer it was being released from the open valve. Approximately 500 gallons of sodium hydroxide was released and was able to migrate to a nearby storm drain that leads to a retention pond. First Call Environmental and Apex Environmental responded to the scene and are handling the on-going remediation.

column168: ON FRIDAY MARCH 6TH 2020, 28 CARBOYS OF UN1993 WASTE FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS, N.O.S.(METHANOL,ISOPROPANOL) WERE PICKED UP FROM JERSEY CITY MEDICAL CENTER. THEY WERE STACKED ON A PALLET, 9 TO A LAYER. THERE WAS ONE CARBOY ON THE 4TH LAYER. THE SKID WAS SHRINK WRAPPED AND PLACED ALONG THE TRUCK WALL BUT IT WAS NOT SECURED TO THE WALL. DURING TRANSIT, THE LOAD SHIFTED AND THE CARBOY ON THE TOP LAYER FELL ON ITS CAP. BREAKING THE CAP, AND LEAKING THE CONTAINERS CONTENTS.  THE DRIVER PULLED OVER AFTER HEARING A BANG IN THE BACK OF THE TRUCK. ONCE PULLED OVER, THE DRIVER NOTICED WASTE LEAKING OUT OF THE SIDE OF THE TRUCK, THROUGH THE FLOOR BOARDS. SPILL PADS WERE PLACED ON THE GROUND TO ABSORB LEAKING WASTE. AN ER TEAM WAS CALLED AND WHEN THEY ARRIVED ON SCENE, THEY OVERPACKED THE LEAKING CONTAINER, CLEANED THE INSIDE OF THE TRUCK, AND SECURED THE LOAD. OUR DRIVER THEN CONTINUED HIS ROUTE.

column168: DRIVER WAS IN 65 MPH SPEED ZONE AND WAS DAY DREAMING WHEN HE WENT INTO A 50 MPH SPEED ZONE ON A CURVE. UNIT DRIFTED OFF THE ROADWAY AND BLACK-TOP SHOULDER, THE WHEELS DROPPED ONTO THE SOFT SOIL AND IT DRAGGED THE UNIT INTO THE DITCH AND ROLLED OVER 3/4 TURN. ONTO PASSENGER SIDE, ONTO TOP AND CAME TO REST ON THE DRIVERS SIDE. DRIVER WAS PINNED IN AND HAD TO BE EVACUATED BY CUTTING OFF THE ROOF OF THE TRUCK. HE WAS UNHARMED AND ENTERED AN AMBULANCE TO BE CHECKED OUT AND WAS RELEASED. DOME COVER ON COMPARTMENT 4 WAS LEAKING AND THE FIRST RESPONDERS WHERE ABLE TO CAPTURE MOST OF THE SPILLING PRODUCT WITH A PIECE OF TIN FUNNELED TO 5 GALLON PAILS AND PUT IN 50 GALLON DRUMS. AN ESTIMATED 150 TO 200 GALLONS WAS SPILLED ONTO THE SOIL. NO SEWER OR WATERWAYS WERE IN THIS LOCATION.  ESTIMATED TIME OF RELEASE WAS 3 1/2 HOURS AT MINIMAL LEAKAGE UNTIL WE COULD GET ANOTHER UNIT THERE TO PUMP OFF THE LOAD SO WE COULD GET THE UNIT UPRIGHTED.  COULD NOT UPRIGHT IT WITH THE LOADED ALUMINUM TRAILER IN FEAR THAT IT WOULD OPEN UP AND WE WOULD LOSE ENTIRE LOAD OF 8500 GALLONS.
column169: THIS DRIVER WAS TERMINATED BEACUSE OF THIS ACCIDENT.  OUR COMPANY HAD JUST STARTING TO INSTALL EVENT RECORDERS IN ALL OF OUR TRACTORS.

column168: The posted speed limit on this road is 45 mph. When Jason reached the sharp corner, he was travelling approximately 60 mph. While going around the corner the tires on the passenger side of the tractor went of the road and onto the soft shoulder. This caused the frontend of the tractor to pull towards the ditch. Jason attempted to correct the issue, but it was too late and subsequently loss control of both the tractor and trailer. During the overcorrecting maneuver the trailer actually slid across the roadway and spun the tractor towards the ditch. Once the tractor and trailer entered the ditch, both units rolled and came to a stop.

column168: According to the information obtained , the following occurred.  While loading, one 55-gallon drum of waste oil was punctured by a forklift. (manifest attached) Approximately 5 gallons of free product were released to the asphalt lot and nearby storm drain. Leak was secured , and Clean harbors Environmental was dispatched to perform the cleanup. Upon arrival on site , Clean Harbors inspected the impacted storm drain. Release was contained within drainage system on site, and did not migrate off site or impact state waters. Clean Harbors flushed the drainage system and cleaned the affected lot. One drum of spent absorbents and debris, and three 55-gallon drums of free product were generated during the cleanup.  Disposal was coordinated by Safety Kleen in accordance with local , state, and federal regulations. There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Praxair Distribution Inc. will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures and driver safety to all personnel.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred. While traveling ,  a single - vehicle accident resulted in a tank rollover , which landed tank truck in roadside embankment .  The Local Fire Department responded to assess the site, placed a containment pool beneath the leaking dome lid, and secured the area.  Marion Environmental was dispatched to oversee tank offload and upright of tanker.  Due to the product involved, and potential to impact human health and the environment , product was solidified inside the tanker prior to uprighting, and product offload was not required.  Tank was in tact, approximately 4 gallons of free product were released from the dome lid to containment pool,  and tanker was uprighted without further incident.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.

column168: The Tidewater Transit TWT vehicle was traveling Dillon Street, and the vehicle left the roadway to the right . After leaving the roadway , the vehicle overturned.  The overturn  caused the tank trailer to rupture , resulting the loss of an estimated 500 gallons of cargo waste liquid. The released liquid impacted a roadside ditch and a field , where it was contained. Pooled liquid was recovered on the date of the incident using a vacuum truck, and transferred to a waiting TWT tanker.  Remaining liquid in the tank trailer was transferred to the replacement TWT tanker.  The liquid was then transported to the designated disposal facility in Deer Park , TX.  Impacted soil was excavated, containerized in lined roll- off containers, and transported to the designated disposal facility in Deer Park, TX for disposal.  The area was restored to pre-existing conditions.   The release was reported to the National Response  Center at 17:39 hours on 03-01-2020.  The release was also reported to the South Carolina Department of Health and Environmental Control on 03/01/2020.  Surface water bodies were neither impacted nor threatened by the release.  Copies of police and fire reports for this incident have been formally requested, but were not available as of the date of this report.
column169: Reminder to drivers too use caution and drive defensively.

column168: At 1110 on March 23, 2020, Kansas City Southern Railway (KCS) personnel working in the Beaumont, TX rail yard observed liquid coming from the dome of tank car TILX 100353 (loaded , UN1832, SULPHURIC  ACID , SPENT ). The KCS Environmental & Hazmat Department mobilized a railroad qualified emergency response contractor to investigate and secure the leaking car.  Upon arrival, responders found the rupture disc on the car had ruptured . A specific event which caused this unknown , but based on condition of the disc, it appeared that the disc had not been serviced / replaced in quite some time and potentially just failed.  A new rupture disc was installed, and the tank car and impacted area neutralized prior to releasing the car back into transportation. File note; Item 19-the quantity released was estimated based on the best information available at the time of filing. This shipment was offered as a bulk shipment , aka one car load, therefore the exact amount offered in this package is not known to the carrier.  This carrier does not have access to mass balance data which can exactly quantity this value.
column169: The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels.  They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs  are troublesome to all because they are, by and large , preventable.  For non accident releases (aka package closure issues such as this ) the shipper is requested to conduct a root cause investigation to determine the causes of release and to then facilities corrective actions to Steve McNealy, KCS Railway, P.O. Box 219335. Kansas City, MO 64121.  The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NAR's.

column168: On March 6,2020, personnel at the above-referenced R+L Carriers(RLC) facility discovered one (1) 55-gallon drum of printing ink(UN1210) had been damaged and released approximately 35 gallons of printing ink to the trailer interior and the tires below the trailer. RLC retained Cura Emergency Services, LC(CES) to manage the cleanup. CES dispatched a crew from Environmental Restoration, LLC(ER) to initiate corrective actions. On March 6,2020, at approximately 10:36 a.m. CST, a crew from ER arrived onsite. Following a site assessment, ER personnel noted approximately 35 gallons of printing ink(UN1210) had been released to the trailer interior and tires below the trailer. The crew further noted the trailer full of cargo. ER personnel removed the cargo from the trailer and containerized the one(1) damaged 55-gallon drum of printing ink into one(1) 85-gallon metal overpack. ER personnel then cut the impacted pallets and containerized into 55-gallon drums. The crew scraped the printing ink from the tires.· ER personnel then deployed granular absorbents to the printing ink-impacted trailer interior and worked in with hand tools until no visual or olfactory evidence of printing ink remained onsite. All printing ink-impacted material and damaged 55-gallon drum were collected in three(3) 55-gallon drums and one(1) 85-gallon metal overpack for transport and disposal as hazardous. ER personnel secured the site and demobilized.

column42: CARTRIDGES FOR WEAPONS, INERT PROJECTILE OR CARTRIDGES, SMALL ARMS
column168: During AM sort operations start at tne ABEA station Bethelem PA discovered a FedEx Envelope containing two boxes 9f small arms ammunition. The contents included a small plastic box with 100 Remington 22 Viper Rimfire Cartridges and a small cardboard box with 50 normaUSA TAC22 22 Long Rifle Rimfire Cartridges. There were no DG markings or labeling on the package, no Shippers Declaration for Dangerous Goods, and no indication of DG on the airbill. The involved package was held at the destination station.
